## Goal: 
Parser should only normalize obvious date-values and mark every unclear Value as unsupported or ambigiuous.

## Supported Inputs:

Whole date: 2020-03-15, 15.03.2020, etc. -> Normalization: 2024-03-15
Year-Month: 2020-03, March 2020, etc. -> 2020-03
Year: 2020 -> 2020
Interval with whole values: 2020-01-01 to 2020-31-12, 01.01.2020 - 31.12.2020, etc. -> 2020-01-01/2020-12-31
Partial Interval: 2020-2021, January 2020 - March 2020, etc. -> 2020/2021, 2020-01/2021-03
ISO: 2020-01-01/2020-12-31 -> 2020-01-01/2020-31-12
W3C/ISO-Timestamp: 2020-03-15T10:30:00Z -> 2020-03-15 or whole timestamp

## Parsing Rules

Parser should work step by step
1. Preprocessing
    Normalize whitespace
    Unify dashes: "-" "—" "–"
    Detect known separators: to, until, bis, /, -
    Case normalization but keep original as evidence
2. Point Date Detection
    Detect ISO-Formats YYYY-MM-DD, YYYY-MM, YYYY
    Detect local formats: DD.MM.YYYY, MM/DD/YYYY, etc.
    Detect Month names in obvious patterns: March 2020, 15 March 2020
3. Interval Detection
    Two parsable Date-values with "range-separator" form an interval
    Both sides may have different precision: 2020-01/2021
    Do not normalize open intervals, mark them as ambiguous or unsupported: since 2020
4. Partial Dates
    YYYY remains year
    YYYY-MM remains year-month
    do NOT add values: 2024 -> 2024-01-01

## Not Supported Inputs

Free text without clear date: during the project -> unsupported (might not be possible due to already existing rules for metadata)
Relative time-values: last year, recently, etc. -> unsupported
Unclear historical values: around 1990, early 20th century, etc. -> unsupported or ambiguous
Seasonal values: summer 2020 -> unsupported
Unclear intervals: 2020 onwards, since 2020 -> unsupported
Conflicting data: created 2020, updated 2022, published 2023 -> ambiguous (Might be irrelevant due to field context of metadata)
Data-values without year: March 15 -> unsupported
Non-Gregorian or cultural values: Ramadan 2020, Q1 2020 -> unsupported

## Confidence Rules

HIGH: structured value or obvious ISO-Date
MEDIUM: clearly parsable value from free text: published March 2020
LOW: date detectable but context is weak or multiple meanings

## Ambiguity Flags

MULTIPLE_DATES_FOUND
CONFLICTING_DATE_EVIDENCE: Multiple sources provide different values.
OPEN_ENDED_INTERVAL: since 2020.
UNSUPPORTED_FREE_TEXT: May already be covered by existing metadata rules.
DATE_WITHOUT_YEAR
RELATIVE_DATE: last year (may already be covered by existing metadata rules).
APPROXIMATE_DATE: around 1990 (may already be covered by existing metadata rules).
